      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, a drippy faucet, a common annoyance indeed! You may need a few tools, such as a wrench, screwdrivers, and possibly some plumber's tape. First, turn off the water supply to the sink. Then, remove the handle by unscrewing it, and you should see a screw underneath. Once you've removed the screw, you can take off the handle and inspect the valve seat. If the seat is worn out, you might need to replace it or clean it with a small brush. If the seat looks fine, you may need to replace the washer or the entire cartridge. Remember, if you're unsure of any step, consult a professional plumber. After fixing it, don't forget to turn the water supply back on and test the faucet. Good luck, and may your sink be free of drips soon!",
